The Science of Skipping: Why We Ignore Social Media Ads

Taji Singh

Observing Ad Skipping Behavior

{alt= “Scatter plot showing the y-axis indicates whether the ad was skipped within 15 seconds (TRUE or FALSE). The x-axis shows four content types: Image, Mixed, Text, and Video. Each point represents an ad, colored by platform: Facebook (Face), Instagram (Inst), Other, TikTok (Tikt), Twitter (Twit), and YouTube (Yout). Larger orange triangles at the bottom of each content type show counts of unskipped ads.}

Key Insights: - Most skipped ads (TRUE) are associated with Mixed and Video content types. - Image and Text content types have fewer ads and a mix of skipped and not skipped results. - TikTok (blue) shows highest skip rates for Video content
- The Orange triangles represent the volume of non-skipped ads, and their larger size under Mixed indicates a higher count of unskipped ads for that content type.

Temporal Patterns in Ad Delivery

{alt=A Line graph shows the x-axis ranges from 0 to 23 (representing the hour of the day), and the y-axis shows the number of ads. Each point is marked with a pink dot, and they are connected with a light blue line.} Key Insights: - There is a peak Ad delivery which occurs at 10 AM and 11 AM, with a sharp spike around these hours, with around 28 number of ads an hour. - Lower ad delivery is seen in the early morning (e.g., 6–8 AM) and late evening (e.g., after 8 PM) with less than 5 number of ads an hour. - This suggests that there is a morning focus in ad scheduling, possibly targeting early-day social media users.

Dominant Ad Formats!

{alt= A Bar chart which shows the x-axis displays four content types: Mixed, Video, Image, and Text. The y-axis shows the count of ads for each type. Bars are colored bright green, with numeric labels on top.}

Key Insights: - Mixed content ads dominate with 44 ads, making it the most frequently used format. - Video content follows with 12 ads, then Image (5 ads) and Text (3 ads). - The chart conveys that advertisers heavily prefer Mixed formats, potentially due to their effectiveness in engaging users across platforms.

Summary:

These visualizations provide insights into:

  • We can see User behavior (skip rates) based on content type and platform.
  • We are able to determine Temporal trends in ad delivery, highlighting optimal posting hours.
  • From the data we can see Prevalent ad formats, showing advertiser preferences.
